COMP 2012 Object-Oriented Programming and Data Structures


Lab 6 Mathematical Foundations of Neural Networks


Introduction

Artificial intelligence (AI) stands at the forefront of technological innovation. Central to the mechanics of AI, especially in neural networks, are matrix operations—essential processes that form the backbone of AI functionalities. Don't worry, you don't need to understand neural networks in order to complete the lab tasks :D. In this lab, we embark on a journey to construct a matrix operation library utilizing templates and operator overloading. This foundational work enables us to carry out key matrix operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and inversion on a variety of data types. Ultimately, this will allow you to implement computations for a single-layer linear model, laying the groundwork for more advanced neural network architectures.


Class Description

The class Matrix encapsulates a two-dimensional matrix of elements, with operations that can be performed on such matrices. It is a template class that uses the placeholder typename T to denote the type of elements stored in the matrix, allowing for a flexible implementation that can handle various data types (e.g., integers, floating points). The class is designed to manage the underlying memory of the matrix dynamically and provides a comprehensive suite of operations including matrix addition, subtraction, multiplication, and inversion. 


Data Members:
size_t is a type used to represent sizes and counts. It is an unsigned integer type. 
- rows: representing the number of rows in the matrix.
- cols: representing the number of columns in the matrix.

- data: Pointer to the first element of an array that stores the matrix elements in row-major order.
- dummy: dummy value for out-of-bounds access

Constructor:
- Matrix(size_t rows, size_t cols): 
Constructs a matrix with the specified number of rows and columns, initializing the elements to their default value.
- Matrix() : 
Default constructor creates an invalid matrix.

Copy Constructor:
- Matrix(const Matrix& other):
Initializes a new Matrix object as a deep copy of an existing Matrix object, copying all elements.

Destructor:
- ~Matrix(): 
Deallocates the dynamically allocated memory used to store the matrix elements.

Assignment Operator:
- Matrix& operator=(const Matrix& other): 
Replaces the current Matrix's contents with the contents of another Matrix, handling self-assignment safely.

Access Operators:
- T& operator()(size_t row, size_t col) and const T& operator()(size_t row, size_t col) const: 
Provides read and write access to the element at the specified row and colum.

Output Operator:
- friend std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Matrix& matrix): 
Enables the printing of the matrix to an output stream, formatting the output as rows and columns of elements.

Mathematical Operations:
- Matrix operator+(const Matrix& rhs) const: Implements matrix addition.
- Matrix operator-(const Matrix& rhs) const: Implements matrix subtraction.
- Matrix operator*(const Matrix& rhs) const: Implements matrix multiplication.
- Matrix operator~() const: Calculates the inverse of a 2x2 matrix.

Working Example

Here is a working example. (This main.cpp is provided in the skeleton code) 
#include "matrix.h"
#include <iostream>

int main() {

    std::cout << "\n================================Case1================================\n";
    // case 1 Constructing copying and printing matrices
    Matrix<int> mat1(2, 2);
    mat1(0, 0) = 1; mat1(0, 1) = 2;
    mat1(1, 0) = 10; mat1(1, 1) = 4;

    Matrix<double> mat2(2, 2);
    mat2(0, 0) = 5; mat2(0, 1) = 4.3;
    mat2(1, 0) = 3.7; mat2(1, 1) = 8.2;

    Matrix<double> mat3(2, 2);
    mat3 = mat2;

    std::cout << "Matrix 1:\n" << mat1 << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Matrix 2:\n" << mat2 << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Matrix 3:\n" << mat3 << std::endl;
    std::cout << "\n================================Case2================================\n";

    // case 2 Addition and Substraction operation

    Matrix<double> matA(4, 4);
    Matrix<double> matB(4, 4);

    for (size_t i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
        for (size_t j = 0; j < 4; ++j) {
            matA(i, j) = i * 4 + j + 1; 
        }
    }

    for (size_t i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
        for (size_t j = 0; j < 4; ++j) {
            matB(i, j) = (i * 4 + j + 1) * 2; 
        }
    }

    std::cout << "Matrix A:\n" << matA << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Matrix B:\n" << matB << std::endl;

    Matrix<double> sumResult = matA + matB;

    std::cout << "Result of Addition:\n" << sumResult << std::endl;


    Matrix<double> subtractionResult = matA - matB;

    std::cout << "Result of Subtraction:\n" << subtractionResult << std::endl;

    std::cout << "\n================================Case3================================\n";

    // case 3 Multiplication operation
        
    Matrix<double> matC(2, 3); // Matrix of 2 rows and 3 columns
    matC(0, 0) = 1; matC(0, 1) = 2; matC(0, 2) = 3;
    matC(1, 0) = 4; matC(1, 1) = 5; matC(1, 2) = 6;

    Matrix<double> matD(3, 2); // Matrix of 3 rows and 2 columns
    matD(0, 0) = 7; matD(0, 1) = 8;
    matD(1, 0) = 9; matD(1, 1) = 10;
    matD(2, 0) = 11; matD(2, 1) = 12;

    std::cout << "Matrix C:\n" << matC << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Matrix D:\n" << matD << std::endl;


    Matrix<double> multiplicationResult = matC * matD;
    
    std::cout << "Multiplication Result:\n" << multiplicationResult << std::endl;



    std::cout << "\n================================Case4================================\n";

    // case 4 Inversion operation (valid only for 2x2 matrices)

    Matrix<double> matInvertible(2, 2);
    matInvertible(0, 0) = 4; matInvertible(0, 1) = 7;
    matInvertible(1, 0) = 2; matInvertible(1, 1) = 6;


    std::cout << "Original Matrix:\n" << matInvertible << std::endl;
    Matrix<double> inverseResult = ~matInvertible;

    std::cout << "Inversion Result:\n" << inverseResult << std::endl;
}

Tasks

You are required to add appropriate lines of code at 5 different places in matrix.h

In this lab we have the following assumpations:
  • For addition and subtraction, both matrices have the same number of rows and columns.
  • For multiplication, the number of columns in the first matrix matches the number of rows in the second matrix.
  • For inversion, we only apply it to invertible and 2x2 matrices
TODO 1: Implement the assignment operator for the Matrix class.
  • This operator should replace the current Matrix's contents with the contents of another Matrix.
TODO 2: Implement the output operator to print the matrix to an ostream.
  • You should iterate over each element of the matrix, printing each row on a new line. Each element should be separated by a space.
TODO 3: Implement operators for addition and subtraction in matrix computation.
  • TODO3.1 Implement the addition operator to add two matrices. We assume both matrices have the same dimensions before performing the addition.
  • TODO3.2 Implement the subtraction operator to subtract one matrix from another. We assume both matrices have the same dimensions before performing the subtraction.

Submission Requirement

The skeleton code can be downloaded from HERE.

You are required to implement the matrix.h and sumbit it.

A main.cpp and its expected output are provided in the skeleton code to test your implementation. The public test on ZINC is using the same main.cpp provided to you in the skeleton code, but ZINC will compile it with memory leakage check enabled.

For this lab, please submit the following file to ZINC:

  • matrix.h

The lab assignment is due 10 minutes after the end of your lab session.

Basic Code Usages

A Makefile is provided to you in the skeleton code: type make compile your code.

Alternatively, you can use the following command:

g++ -std=c++11 main.cpp -o lab6.exe

For debuging and memory leakage check, use:

g++ -std=c++11 -g -fsanitize=address,leak,undefined main.cpp -o lab6.exe

And then run the program with:

./lab6.exe
